   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_unknown_01_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinS1">Miss Brinkley</persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               We are all anxious to<lb/>
               know how dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</persName><lb/>
               is, and how she bears the<lb/>
               loss, which under the most<lb/>
               alleviating circumstances,<lb/>
               is always most painful<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               From what you said<lb/>
               of your uncle's having<lb/>
               long suffered from ill<lb/>
               health - it is I trust some<lb/>
               consolation to his friend<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_unknown_01_page02.jpg"/>
               that he is relieved from<lb/>
               a life of tedious illness;<lb/>
               but I know well what<lb/>
               such a heart as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkleys</persName><lb/>
               must feel at the total<lb/>
               separation from a long loved<lb/>
               brother. Will you have<lb/>
               the kindness to write me<lb/>
               a line to tell me about<lb/>
               her - &amp; will you give her<lb/>
               all our love &amp; assure<lb/>
               her of the sympathy of<lb/>
               all her friends of this<lb/>
               House -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_6931_unknown_01_page03.jpg"/>
               A little packet from<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthstown</placeName> has this<lb/>
               moment been left here<lb/>
               for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Brinkley</persName> - The<lb/>
               first time you are in<lb/>
               town will you be so<lb/>
               good as to call for it<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I am very glad you<lb/>
               have <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. J. Brinkley</persName> with<lb/>
               you now, it must be such<lb/>
               a comfort to your moth<unclear>er</unclear><lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Believe me dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinS1">Miss B</persName>,<lb/>
               yours affect.<hi rend="superscript">ly</hi><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">H Beaufort</persName><note type="certainty">Though it remains unclear by which Beaufort sister this letter was written, it seems likely that it was written by Honora Beaufort due to relationship proximity to the Edgeworths and, subsequently, the Brinkleys.</note><lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>Thursday</p><lb/>
            </postscript>
